<td valign="top" class="postbody">
<hr />
Folks:
<br />

<br />
I'm getting very interested in locating and documenting &quot;missing&quot;, &quot;lost&quot;, or &quot;destroyed&quot; cemeteries as a sub-specialization of this cemetery photography pursuit. 
<br />

<br />
Do you know of a good book or web site on the burial practices of the early to mid-1800s? What I'm looking foris a way to think like an 1800s Ohio pioneer, looking at a plot of land and deciding where to start planting my newly-departed family members as croak. This for family plots, rather than community/church plots. 
<br />

<br />
What's got me thinking like this is my hunt for Courtwright (Courtright?) Cemetery in Concord Township, Delaware County Ohio. I know approximately where it was reported as being, but searchers in 1987 were unable to locate it.  It's on a fairly large plot of land. I have a map that shows the property lines of the plots owned by the Courtwright family in 1866, but I'm not sure that it will limit the area of search enough - just give me a smarter idea of where to start looking. A great deal of the Courtwright land was covered with water (&quot;Twin Lakes&quot;) when they built  O'Shaughnessy Dam in 1924. However &quot;Courtright Cemetery&quot;
<br />
was mapped by the WPA project in the late 30's (albeit as being only &quot;0.01 acres&quot;, which seems to generally indicate only one or two graves)   so it's wasn't under water.  When the Twin Lakes park area was built, it might have been destroyed, though, depending on where it was. 
<br />

<br />
The search area for Courtwright is a brush-covered patch which has never had any buildings on it, owned by the City of Columbus Ohio. I'm planning a visual, non-destructive search, followed perhaps by a &quot;probe-the earth&quot; search for shallowly-buried stones with a dowel. This is all a thought exercise at present, and I intend to involve the City of Columbus and the Delaware County Historical Society in the planning before doing anything. It's a low-budget project, so I don't plan to be buying any ground-penetrating radar satellite time!
<br />

<br />
I *think*, from seeing various cemeteries and looking at their locations on topo maps, that they would pick a spot overlooking water if possible) and a spot higher rather than lower in elevation (if possible), but I don't know if they thought like that at all or if I'm just projecting my own thoughts on the process. I also assume they'd keep the graves on their own property (as owned at that time).
<br />

<br />
Thoughts anyone?
<br />

<br />
In addition to Courtright, I have interest in pursuing a &quot;destroyed&quot; cemetery (Hensel, in Jerome Township, Union County Ohio), where the stone(s) for mid-1800s graves were reportedly pushed into a creek in the 1980s along with the debris from the demolition of an old schoolhouse. Finding the stones would be the goal, using research of news coverage of the demolition, personal interviews with construction folk (if possible), and interviews with residents of the area. It's possible that the stone(s) and remains were moved to another local cemetery and that the reports of bulldozing on the web are incorrect. The area of the old school is now a community park.
<br />

<br />
There is another local case (Depp Cemetery, Concord Township, Delaware County Ohio) where stones were removed from an historic early 1800s cemetery for cleanup in the 1930s and then &quot;misplaced&quot; by the Township. Only one stone was left on the site. The Delaware County Historical Society's expert on my Township thinks that the stones were likely stored in someone's garage or barn, and may still be in the area. The goal is finding the stones and arranging to have them returned to the cemetery site.
<br />

<br />
All three of these sites are within a mile or so of my house!
<br />

<br />

<br />
Jeff</td>
