<td valign="top" class="postbody">
<hr />
Most of the older cemeteries, particularly family ones, that I've visited are almost always on a knoll or hilltop.  Granted, I'm from West Virginia, so it's hard not to find a knoll or hilltop to build the cemetery on.  Anyhow, my grandmother used to always tell me the main reason they did it was to keep water out of the graves.  If a tomb was low in a valley, the water table would be closer to the surface and more likely to flood Uncle Jim-Bob's casket in a heavy rain.  Up on the hillside, the water would run off of Aunt Millie's grave down into the valley, leaving her casket dry.
<br />

<br />
If you think about it, in today's age, it really doesn't matter much, as modern cemeteries use steel or aluminum vaults that lock down with an airtight seal.  But, 50-100 years ago, when the only choices were pine, oak, or mahogany... water could definitely pose a problem.
<br />

<br />
I've also been one who believes another reason they were up on hillside was because it was usually a peaceful place.  Somewhere you can go and get away from things, have a nice view, and just spend time remembering your loved ones.  That's just my twist.</td>
</tr>
