<td valign="top" class="postbody">
<hr />
Actually, the erosion thing was a possibility.  Again, going back to conversations with my grandmother many years ago...  she told me about one cemetery where the hill caved in and caskets were literally sticking out of the hillside.  Of course, this is another West Virginia issue... the area where my grandmother was from was just full of coal mines.  Back in the day when there weren't regulations or hi-tech mapping systems.  These guys just cut miles and miles of mines deep in the mountains, following the coal seams wherever they went.  When the seam ended, they moved out of the mine and started another one... leaving the last one to rot.  Even today, there are places you can drive by in WV where a hillside will just slide in all at once because a long forgotten mine finally caved in.  As I recall my grandmother telling this, that was why the hillside at this particular cemetery gave way.
<br />

<br />
My grandmother was born in 1909, so this would have probably happened around 1915-1920.</td>
</tr>
