<td valign="top" class="postbody">
<hr />
We had that coal mine collapse problem in Coshocton County every once in a while. Not nearly as bad as parts of West Virginia but it was fairly common. A section of the Southeast side of the City of Coshocton has several underground mines that either cause sink holes or water problems for the newer homes in that area. Some of the homes out in there are $300,000+ so needless to say the owners aren't very happy about the fact that their homes are built over abandoned mines. The houses were built in the 70's, 80's, 90's and 2000's so nobody even thought about the possibility of abandoned mines. 150 years go that area wasn't even close to being inside the city limits.</td>
</tr>
