<table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr><td><span class="genmed"><strong>WVOz1970 wrote:</strong></span></td></tr><tr><td class="quote">Most of the older cemeteries, particularly family ones, that I've visited are almost always on a knoll or hilltop.  
<br />

<br />
I've also been one who believes another reason they were up on hillside was because it was usually a peaceful place.  Somewhere you can go and get away from things, have a nice view, and just spend time remembering your loved ones.  That's just my twist.</td></tr></table>
<br />

<br />
The area of the Courtright Cemetery I'm hunting has also changed in nature since it was established, with the building of a dam on the Scioto river in 1924 that flooded the small ravine which would be overlooked by the search area. Unfortunately, I don't have topo maps from the mid-1850s (I guess that their GPS units wouldn't work until AA batteries were invented   <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" /> ).
<br />

<br />
It's still possible that some of the older folks in the area may have a memory of where the small cemetery was located - it was logged by WPA in the late 1930s, and likely survived beyond that. Kids play *everywhere*! 
<br />

<br />
My barber shop also handles a lot of &quot;blue hairs&quot; and &quot;grey hairs&quot; from the neighborhood, so I'm going to recruit the folks there to ask them about the local cemeteries. The shop has a bulletin board with several articles which include some history of Depp Cemetery and it's ties to the Underground Railroad, so they have an interest in local history. The search for Courtwright Cemetery should be right up their alley.</td>
